@article{White1998,
abstract = {The Antarctic circumpolar wave (ACW) is a nominal 4-yr climate signal in$\backslash$nthe ocean-atmosphere systemin the Southern Ocean, propagating eastward$\backslash$nat an average speed of 6-8 cm s(-1), composed of two waves taking$\backslash$napproximately 8 years to circle the globe. The ACW is characterized by a$\backslash$npersistent phase relationship between warm (cool) sea surface$\backslash$ntemperature (SST) anomalies and poleward (equatorward) meridional$\backslash$nsurface wind (MSW) anomalies. Recently, White and Chen demonstrated that$\backslash$nSST anomalies in the Southern Ocean operate to induce anomalous vortex$\backslash$nstretching in the lower troposphere that is balanced by the anomalous$\backslash$nmeridional advection of planetary vorticity, yielding MSW anomalies as$\backslash$nobserved. In the present study, the authors seek to understand how this$\backslash$natmospheric response to SST anomalies produces a positive feedback to$\backslash$nthe ocean (i.e., an anomalous SST tendency displaced eastward of SST$\backslash$nanomalies) that both maintains the ACW against dissipation and accounts$\backslash$nfor its eastward propagation. To achieve this, we couple a global$\backslash$nequilibrium climate model for the lower troposphere to a global heat$\backslash$nbudget model for the upper ocean. In the absence of coupling, the model$\backslash$nAntarctic Circumpolar Current (ACC) advects SST anomalies from initial$\backslash$nconditions to the east at speeds slower than observed, taking 12-14$\backslash$nyears to circle the globe with amplitudes that become insignificant$\backslash$nafter 6-8 years. In the presence of coupling, eastward speeds of the$\backslash$nmodel ACC are matched by those due to coupling, together yielding a$\backslash$nmodel ACW of a nominal 4-yr period composed of two waves that circle the$\backslash$nglobe in approximately 8 years, as observed. Feedback from atmosphere to$\backslash$nocean works through the anomalous zonal surface wind response to SST$\backslash$nanomalies, yielding poleward Ekman how anomalies in phase with warm SST$\backslash$nanomalies. As such, maintenance of the model ACW is achieved through a$\backslash$nbalance between anomalous meridional Ekman heat advection and anomalous$\backslash$nsensible-plus-latent heat loss to the atmosphere. This balance requires$\backslash$nthe alignment of covarying SST and MSW anomalies to be tilted into the$\backslash$nsouthwest-northeast direction, which accounts for the spiral structure$\backslash$nobserved in global SST and sea level pressure anomaly patterns around$\backslash$nthe Southern Ocean. Eastward coupling speeds of the model ACW derive$\backslash$nfrom a beta effect in coupling that displaces a portion of the anomalous$\backslash$nmeridional Ekman heat advection, and its corresponding anomalous SST$\backslash$ntendency, to the east of SST anomalies. Therefore, the ACW is an example$\backslash$nof self-organization within the global ocean-atmosphere system,$\backslash$ndepending upon the spherical shape of the rotating earth for its$\backslash$npropagation and the mean meridional SST gradient for its maintenance,$\backslash$nand producing a net poleward eddy heat flux in the upper ocean that$\backslash$ntends to reduce this mean gradient.},
