@article{Cai1999,
abstract = {Variability in the southern atmospheric circulation at mid- to high$\backslash$nlatitudes with a dominant quasi-stationary wavenumber-3 pattern has been$\backslash$nreported in many observational studies. The variability is barotropic in$\backslash$nnature with signals in the middle troposphere as well as at the$\backslash$natmosphere-ocean interface. Moreover, there are preferred Fixed centers$\backslash$nfor the strongest anomalies. These features are well reproduced by the$\backslash$nCommonwealth Scientific and Industrial Research Organisation coupled$\backslash$nmodel on various timescales. On the interannual timescale. an index of$\backslash$nthe modeled wavenumber-3 pattern shows little correlation with the$\backslash$nmodeled Southern Oscillation index, suggesting that the variability$\backslash$nassociated with wavenumber 3 anomalies is separate to modeled ENSO-like$\backslash$nevents. However, the variation of the pattern index is strikingly$\backslash$nsimilar to, and highly correlated with, the modeled oceanic variability.$\backslash$nThe associated oceanic anomalies move eastward and are similar to those$\backslash$nof the observed Antarctic circumpolar wave (ACW). The modeled ACW-like$\backslash$nanomalies exist not only at the surface but also through middle ocean$\backslash$ndepths, with a similar barotropic nature to those of the atmospheric$\backslash$nanomalies. The oceanic anomalies also display a wavenumber-3 pattern.$\backslash$nThe essential elements of the dynamics of the modeled ACW are the$\backslash$nadvection of SST anomalies by the surface Antarctic Circumpolar Current$\backslash$n(ACC), and the interactions between anomalies of SST and mean sea level$\backslash$npressure (MSLP). Associated with the standing wavenumber-3 pattern,$\backslash$nthere are fixed centers for the strongest MSLP anomalies. As a positive$\backslash$nSST anomaly advected by surface ACC approaches a center of a positive$\backslash$nMSLP anomaly, the MSLP decreases. The positive (negative) SST anomalies$\backslash$nare generated by anomalous latent and heat fluxes, which are in turn$\backslash$ninduced by southward (northward) meridional wind stress anomalies$\backslash$nresulting from geostrophic balance. These MSLP anomalies change sign$\backslash$nwhen the positive (negative) SST anomalies move to a location near the$\backslash$ncenters. Once MSLP anomalies change sign, positive (negative) SST$\backslash$nanomalies are generated again reinforcing the anomalies entering from$\backslash$nthe west. The time for the surface ACC to advect one-sixth of the$\backslash$ncircuit around the pole corresponds to the time of a half-cycle of the$\backslash$nstanding MSLP oscillations. Thus the surface ACC determines the$\backslash$nfrequency of the standing oscillation. In the present model, the speed$\backslash$nof the surface ACC is such that the period of the standing oscillation$\backslash$nis 4-5 yr, and it would take 12-16 yr for an anomaly to encircle the$\backslash$npole. These and other features of the modeled ACW, together with$\backslash$nassociated dynamic processes, are analyzed and discussed.},
